    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Elderberry Gummies for Kids</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Are elderberry gummies safe for kids?</summary><p>Commercially prepared elderberry gummies from Sambucus nigra are generally safe for children 2+ when used at recommended doses. Raw elderberries are toxic but processing eliminates harmful compounds. A 2019 review found no significant adverse effects in pediatric elderberry studies. Always follow age-specific dosing on the label.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do elderberry gummies actually help kids get sick less?</summary><p>Evidence is promising. A 2019 meta-analysis found elderberry reduced upper respiratory infection duration and severity. A 2004 study found elderberry syrup reduced flu duration by 4 days. Most trials are in adults; pediatric data is limited but encouraging. Elderberry is not a vaccine substitute.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What age can kids start taking elderberry gummies?</summary><p>Most elderberry gummies are labeled for ages 2+. Children under 2 should not take gummies without pediatrician approval. For toddlers 2-3, consider cutting gummies to reduce choking risk. Elderberry syrups may be safer for children under 4.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much elderberry should kids take?</summary><p>Follow the product's age-specific dosing. Typically 1-2 gummies for ages 2-6, and 2-3 gummies for ages 7-12. Most kids' gummies provide 50-100mg elderberry extract per gummy. Some practitioners suggest doubling during acute illness for 3-5 days — consult your pediatrician.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can kids take elderberry gummies every day?</summary><p>Yes, daily use during cold and flu season is common and safe at recommended doses. Some families use elderberry year-round. Some pediatricians recommend seasonal cycling: daily October-April, break during summer. No adverse effects from long-term daily use have been documented.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do elderberry gummies interact with medications?</summary><p>Elderberry may interact with immunosuppressants (it stimulates immunity), diabetes medications (may lower blood sugar), and diuretics. No known interactions with standard pediatric medications. Consult your pediatrician if your child takes prescription medications.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What should I look for in kids' elderberry gummies?</summary><p>Sambucus nigra species, standardized extract, added vitamin C and zinc, low sugar (2g or less), third-party testing, no artificial colors/flavors, and clear age-appropriate dosing instructions.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are elderberry gummies better than syrup for kids?</summary><p>Both deliver the same compounds when matched for dose. Gummies offer pre-measured dosing and better compliance (kids prefer them). Syrups can be given to younger children (some are labeled 1+). For ages 4+, gummies are typically preferred. For ages 1-3, syrups may be more appropriate.</p></details>

